name: propene, 1,2-dichloro-3,3,3-trifluoro-
Reason: The basic unit for the target molecule would be ethene, which has a melting point of -169°C. The melting point is affected by changes in molecular weight and electronegativity differences. Starting with ethene, we consider the functional groups: Each chlorine atom contributes to an increase in the melting point due to an increase in molecular weight and the dipole it introduces in the molecule. A typical alkyl halide can raise the melting point by approximately +20 to +30°C per halogen atom. We have two chlorines, so we initially estimate an increase of around +40 to +60°C. Each fluorine atom also adds to the melting point by a similar logic, but because fluorine is smaller, its contribution might be slightly less, estimated at +15 to +20°C per fluorine atom. We have three fluorines, giving a rough estimate of +45 to +60°C. Summing these contributions, we predict an increase of +85 to +120°C to the base ethene melting point.
